 A 50-year-old chemistry teacher, who has taught for some 30 years, may be asked to quickly name the Kapenguria Six, the President of Egypt or even how many stores ‘ought’ to be in a school. It is that simple, but the number of those that ‘pass’ the interviews are circumscribed by availability of funds.
These interviews are, of course, a sham and all those teachers qualify, but have to be trimmed down. Those ‘lucky’ enough to pass can become heads of departments or even principals without portfolio.
You just see them as classroom teachers, but they’re yearning to get to head some school. This is the source of a lot of danger and can even get as bad as blackmail, or sabotage.
Imagine a girl school where some 10 teachers in the staffroom qualify to be principal, but are still stuck to obeying the existing head. Add the fact that the incumbent is from another region and has been delocalised just when others are positioning themselves to take over the mantle.



